\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Nominal rate
\series default
 is the variable cost per each period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Spot rate
\series default
 is the annual average cost of money (zero-coupon rate).
 Ths spot rate assumes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locking
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for a certain time period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1+s_{t})^{t}=\Pi_{n=1}^{n=t}(1+i)n\Rightarrow s_{t}=\sqrt[t]{\Pi_{n=1}^{n=t}(1+i_{n})}-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Lump sum
\series default
: instead of asking 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what is the PV
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we look at the future value, by accumulating all the future CFs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As nominal rates go up, spot rates increase as well - but 
\series bold
to a lower extent
\series default
.
